05890nam a22008655i 9780231550420DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019025148  a97802315504207 a10.7312/rols193622doi  a(DE-B1597)541722  a(OCoLC)1110148437  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBR1615b.R65 2019 7aREL0840002bisacsh1 aRolsky, L. Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rise and Fall of the Religious Left :bPolitics, Television, and Popular Culture in the 1970s and Beyond /cL. Benjamin Rolsky. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Series on Religion and Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Religious Liberalism, American Politics, and Public Life -- t1. Norman Lear, the Christian Right, and the Spiritual Politics of the Religious Left -- t2. All in the Family and the Spiritual Politicization of the American Sitcom -- t3. Norman Lear, the FCC, and the Holy War Over American Television -- t4. People for the American Way and Spiritual Politics in Late Twentieth- Century America -- t5. Liberalism as Variety Show: I Love Liberty and the Decline of the Religious Left -- tConclusion: Religion, Politics, and the Public Square-2019 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor decades now, Americans have believed that their country is deeply divided by “culture wars” waged between religious conservatives and secular liberals. In most instances, Protestant conservatives have been cast as the instigators of such warfare, while religious liberals have been largely ignored. In this book, L. Benjamin Rolsky examines the ways in which American liberalism has helped shape cultural conflict since the 1970s through the story of how television writer and producer Norman Lear galvanized the religious left into action.The creator of comedies such as All in the Family and Maude, Lear was spurred to found the liberal advocacy group People for the American Way in response to the rise of the religious right. Rolsky offers engaged readings of Lear’s iconic sitcoms and published writings, considering them as an expression of what he calls the spiritual politics of the religious left. He shows how prime-time television became a focus of political dispute and demonstrates how Lear’s emergence as an interfaith activist catalyzed ecumenical Protestants, Catholics, and Jews who were determined to push back against conservatism’s ascent. Rolsky concludes that Lear’s political involvement exemplified religious liberals’ commitment to engaging politics on explicitly moral grounds in defense of what they saw as the public interest. An interdisciplinary analysis of the definitive cultural clashes of our fractious times, The Rise and Fall of the Religious Left foregrounds the foundational roles played by popular culture, television, and media in America’s religious history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLear, Norman-Influence. 0aLiberalism (Religion)zUnited States. 0aLiberalism (Religion)-United States. 0aLiberalismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aLiberalism-Religious aspects-Christianity. 0aPopular culturexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular culture-Religious aspects-Christianity. 0aPopular culture-United States-History-20th century. 0aReligious right. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook p